'''Jacob Everett Shaffelburg''' (born November 26, 1999) is a Canadian professional [[soccer]] player who plays as a [[winger (association football)|winger]] for [[Major League Soccer]] club [[Los Angeles FC]] and the [[Canada men's national soccer team|Canada national team]].

==Early life==
Shaffelburg played youth soccer for Valley United SC and Team Nova Scotia.<ref name="KCN2018">{{cite news |last1=Thompson |first1=Ashley |title=Living the Dream: 'He has his eyes set on mastery' |url=https://www.saltwire.com/sports/living-the-dream-he-has-his-eyes-set-on-mastery-233154/?location=annapolis-valley |access-date=August 10, 2019 |work=[[SaltWire Network]]|date=August 11, 2018}}</ref> In 2012, he joined FC Nashville Heroes, where he played in the 2012 U.S. Club Soccer National Cup.<ref name="ten">{{cite web|url=https://www.tennessean.com/story/sports/nashvillesc/2022/09/13/nashville-sc-jacob-shaffelburg-loan-toronto-fc/7973246001/|title=He scores goals for Nashville SC — but his connection to the city dates back 10 years|first=Drake|last=Hills|date=September 13, 2022|work=[[The Tennessean]]|access-date=2026-05-04}}</ref> In January 2014, he joined the [[Sporting Kansas City]] Academy, where he played for a month.<ref name=ten /> Shaffelburg demonstrated dominance in cross country running and track and field in his middle school years. He won the NSSAF junior boys 3000m in June, 2014 with a spectacular sub 10 minute performance. College scouts still speculate what levels he could have reached if he stuck with running.

At age 15, he began attending high school in Massachusetts at the [[Berkshire School]], where he played for their highly regarded soccer program.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.mlssoccer.com/post/2019/06/21/toronto-fc-sign-forward-jacob-shaffelburg-homegrown-player-deal |title=Toronto FC sign forward Jacob Shaffelburg to Homegrown Player deal |last=Sigal |first=Jonathan |work=[[Major League Soccer]] |date=June 21, 2019 |access-date=June 21, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/nova-scotia/shaffelburg-soccer-strides-toronto-fc-1.6225106 |title=Nova Scotia's Shaffelburg gains valuable experience with Toronto FC, Team Canada |first=Paul |last=Palmeter |date=October 29, 2021 |work=[[Canadian Broadcasting Corporation|CBC]]}}</ref> He played an instrumental part in the team, scoring four goals in two games in the NEPSAC playoffs his senior year (2018), helping Berkshire win their fifth title in seven years<ref>{{Cite news |last=Hayes |first=Michael |url=https://www.berkshireschool.org/about-us/news/news-at-berkshire/~board/main-news-feed/post/bears-capture-fifth-soccer-title-with-3-1-win-over-worcester-academy |title=Bears Capture Fifth Soccer Title With 3–1 Win Over Worcester Academy |date=November 19, 2018 |work=Berkshire School |access-date=April 6, 2020}}</ref> and he was named 2017&ndash;18 Gatorade Massachusetts Boys Soccer Player of the Year.<ref>{{Cite web |last=Giannis |first=Maniatis |date=2025-03-12 |title=livescore |url=https://livescore.icu/ |access-date=2026-05-04 |language=en}}</ref><ref name="CH2019">{{cite news |title=Port Williams' Shaffelburg signs first-team deal with Toronto FC |url=https://www.thechronicleherald.ca/sports/soccer/port-williams-shaffelburg-signs-first-team-deal-with-toronto-fc-325368/ |access-date=June 29, 2019 |work=[[The Chronicle Herald]] |date=June 21, 2019 |location=[[Halifax, Nova Scotia]]}}</ref> While in the US, he also played youth soccer with [[Manhattan SC]] where he won U.S. Club Soccer U-16 National Championship in 2016.<ref name="tfcii">{{cite web|url=https://www.torontofc.ca/post/2018/11/28/toronto-fc-ii-sign-jacob-shaffelburg |title=Toronto FC II sign Jacob Shaffelburg |date=November 28, 2018 |work=[[Toronto FC]]|access-date=May 22, 2020}}</ref>

He joined the [[Toronto FC Academy]] in 2016.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.torontofc.ca/players/jacob-shaffelburg/|title=Jacob Shaffelburg Toronto FC Profile|work=[[Toronto FC]]|access-date=2026-05-04}}</ref> He appeared in a friendly for the [[HFX Wanderers FC]] Atlantic Selects team in 2018 against [[Fortuna Düsseldorf]]'s U-21 team, where he scored a goal.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://thechronicleherald.ca/sports/1587151-wanderers-win-shootout-thriller-over-fortuna-dusseldorf|title=Wanderers win shootout thriller over Fortuna Dusseldorf|work=The Chronicle Herald|date=July 28, 2018|last=Palov|first=Willy|access-date=July 28, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180729050208/http://thechronicleherald.ca/sports/1587151-wanderers-win-shootout-thriller-over-fortuna-dusseldorf|archive-date=July 29, 2018|url-status=dead}}</ref> He had originally committed to the [[University of Virginia]] on a soccer scholarship, but ultimately decided to sign a professional contract instead.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.wakingthered.com/2018/11/28/18116246/toronto-fc-tfc-ii-add-jacob-shaffelburg-ahead-of-2019-usl-league-one-season-vanney-greg |title=TFC II add Shaffelburg ahead of 2019 USL League One season |last=Grossi |first=James |date=November 28, 2018 |work=Waking The Red |access-date=May 22, 2020 |archive-date=December 4, 2021 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20211204202805/https://www.wakingthered.com/2018/11/28/18116246/toronto-fc-tfc-ii-add-jacob-shaffelburg-ahead-of-2019-usl-league-one-season-vanney-greg |url-status=dead }}</ref>

==Club career==
===Toronto FC II===
He played a game with [[Toronto FC III]] in [[League1 Ontario]] in [[2017 League1 Ontario season|2017]].<ref name=tfcii />

===Black Rock===
In 2018, he played with [[Black Rock FC]] in the [[Premier Development League]]. He finished as the team's leading scorer with eight goals, tied with [[Ifunanyachi Achara]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.benningtonbanner.com/stories/black-rock-fc-wins-pdl-northeast-division-title-in-first-season,544437? |title=Black Rock FC wins PDL Northeast Division title in first season |first=Geoff |last=Smith |date=July 10, 2018 |work=Berkshire Eagle |publisher=Bennington Banner |access-date=May 22, 2020 |url-status=dead}}</ref>

===Return to Toronto FC II===
In November 2018, he signed his first professional contract with [[Toronto FC II]]<ref name=tfcii /> and began the 2019 season with them in [[USL League One]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thechronicleherald.ca/sports/local-sports/shaffelburg-on-soccer-fast-track-with-toronto-fc-339087/|title=Shaffelburg on soccer fast track with Toronto FC|website=The Chronicle Herald|first=Willy |last=Palov|date=August 1, 2019|access-date=August 2, 2019}}</ref>

===Toronto FC===
Shaffelburg made his first appearance for [[Toronto FC]] in the [[2019 CONCACAF Champions League]] on February 19, 2019 and then signed with [[Toronto FC]] as a Homegrown Player on June 21, 2019.<ref name="CH2019"/> He made his first [[Major League Soccer|MLS]] appearance the following day, playing 31 minutes against [[FC Dallas]] in [[Frisco, Texas]].<ref>{{cite news |last1=Buffery |first1=Steve |title=Jacob Shaffelburg climbs the ladder and gets his first taste of MLS action |url=https://torontosun.com/sports/soccer/mls/toronto-fc/jacob-shaffelburg-climbs-the-ladder-and-gets-his-first-taste-of-mls-action |access-date=June 29, 2019 |newspaper=Toronto Sun |date=June 23, 2019}}</ref> Four days later, on June 26, he had his first start for Toronto FC at [[BMO Field]] scoring an assist in a 3–2 win against [[Atlanta United FC]],<ref name="TS2019">{{cite news |last1=Wharnsby |first1=Tim |title=Nova Scotia teen Jacob Shaffelburg impresses in starting debut for TFC |url=https://www.thestar.com/sports/tfc/2019/06/28/nova-scotia-teen-jacob-shaffelburg-impresses-in-starting-debut-for-tfc.html |access-date=June 29, 2019 |work=[[Toronto Star]] |date=June 28, 2019|pages=S6 }}</ref> setting up the fastest goal in TFC history only 29 seconds into the game.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Wharnsby |first1=Tim |title=Toronto FC over Atlanta in a wild ride of late penalty kicks and record fast goals |url=https://www.theglobeandmail.com/sports/soccer/article-toronto-fc-over-atlanta-in-a-wild-ride-of-late-penalty-kicks-and/ |access-date=June 29, 2019 |work=[[The Globe and Mail]] |agency=[[The Canadian Press]] |date=June 26, 2019 |location=Toronto}}</ref> Shaffelburg would quickly find himself in the starting lineup shortly after signing, earning rave reviews for his pace from the coaching staff.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thestar.com/sports/tfc/2019/08/02/teenage-winger-jacob-shaffelburg-rapidly-making-his-name-at-toronto-fc.html|title=Teenage winger Jacob Shaffelburg rapidly making his name at Toronto FC|website=Toronto Star|first=Neil |last=Davidson|date=August 2, 2019|access-date=August 2, 2019}}</ref>

He scored his first goal in the 74th minute on 15 May 2021, in a 1–1 draw against [[New York City FC|New York City]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thestar.com/sports/tfc/2021/05/15/shaffelburgs-goal-pulls-toronto-into-1-1-draw-with-nycfc.html|title=Shaffelburg's goal pulls Toronto into 1–1 draw with NYCFC|date=May 15, 2021|work=[[Toronto Star]]|access-date=2026-05-04}}</ref> On September 3, he was loaned to [[Toronto FC II]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.torontofc.ca/news/toronto-fc-loan-jacob-shaffelburg-to-toronto-fc-ii|title=Toronto FC loan Jacob Shaffelburg to Toronto FC II|date=September 3, 2021|work=[[Toronto FC]]|access-date=2026-05-04}}</ref> Upon completion of the 2021 season, Shaffelburg's option for the 2022 season would be picked up by Toronto.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.torontofc.ca/news/toronto-fc-announce-year-end-roster-decisions?3=&s=09|title=Toronto FC Announce Year-End Roster Decisions|website=Toronto FC|date=December 1, 2021|access-date=2026-05-04}}</ref> He went on a short loan to the second team again in 2022.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.torontofc.ca/news/toronto-fc-loan-jacob-shaffelburg-to-toronto-fc-ii-x1498|title=Toronto FC loan Jacob Shaffelburg to Toronto FC II|date=July 3, 2022|work=[[Toronto FC]]|access-date=2026-05-04}}</ref>

===Nashville SC===
[[File:MIA-NSH US Open Cup Throw in (DeAndre Yedlin and Corentin Jean cropped).jpg|thumb|Shaffelburg (in yellow) playing for Nashville SC 2023]]

In August 2022, Shaffelburg joined [[Nashville SC]] on loan for the remainder of the 2022 season, with an option for a permanent transfer in 2023.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.torontofc.ca/news/toronto-fc-send-jacob-shaffelburg-on-loan-to-nashville-sc-for-gam|date=August 2, 2022|title=Toronto FC send Jacob Shaffelburg on loan to Nashville SC for GAM|work=[[Toronto FC]]|access-date=2026-05-04}}</ref> He made his debut for Nashville on August 21 against [[FC Dallas]] and scored a goal in a 4–0 victory.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.mlssoccer.com/news/nashville-sc-s-playoff-hopes-get-shot-in-the-arm-with-lopsided-win-over-fc-dalla|title=Nashville SC's playoff hopes get "shot in the arm" with lopsided win over FC Dallas|date=August 22, 2022|first=Sydney|last=Hunte|publisher=[[Major League Soccer]]|access-date=2026-05-04}}</ref> After the season, Nashville exercised the purchase option for the 2023 season and signed him to a four-year contract extension with a club option for 2027.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.torontofc.ca/news/toronto-fc-receive-gam-in-exchange-for-jacob-shaffelburg|title=Toronto FC receive GAM in exchange for Jacob Shaffelburg|date=November 16, 2022|publisher=[[Toronto FC]]|access-date=2026-05-04}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://northerntribune.ca/nashville-sc-jacob-shaffelburg/|title=Official: Shaffelburg Inks Four-Year Deal With Nashville|date=November 16, 2022|work=Northern Tribune|first=John|last=Jacques|access-date=2026-05-04}}</ref>

===Los Angeles FC===
On December 29, 2025, Shaffelburg was acquired by [[Los Angeles FC]] from [[Nashville SC]] in exchange for $1,000,000 in General Allocation Money (GAM).<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.lafc.com/news/lafc-acquires-forward-jacob-shaffelburg-from-nashville-sc|title=LAFC Acquires Forward Jacob Shaffelburg from Nashville SC|date=December 29, 2025|publisher=LAFC|access-date=2026-05-04}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.tsn.ca/soccer/article/canada-winger-shaffelburg-dealt-to-lafc/|title=Canada winger Shaffelburg dealt to LAFC |date=December 29, 2025|publisher=LAFC|access-date=2026-05-04}}</ref>

==International career==
===Youth===
Shaffelburg was named to the [[Canada men's national under-23 soccer team|Canadian U-23]] provisional roster for the [[2020 CONCACAF Men's Olympic Qualifying Championship]] on February 26, 2020.<ref>{{cite web |title=Canada Soccer announces Provisional List for Concacaf Men's Olympic Qualifying |url=https://www.canadasoccer.com/canada-soccer-announces-provisional-list-for-concacaf-men-s-olympic-qualifying-p162594-preview-1 |publisher=Canada Soccer |access-date=February 26, 2020 |date=February 26, 2020 |archive-date=March 9, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200309191149/https://www.canadasoccer.com/canada-soccer-announces-provisional-list-for-concacaf-men-s-olympic-qualifying-p162594-preview-1 |url-status=dead }}</ref>

===Senior===
Shaffelburg received his first senior international call-up to Canada on January 3, 2020, for matches against [[Barbados national football team|Barbados]] and [[Iceland national football team|Iceland]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.canadasoccer.com/canada-soccer-s-men-s-national-team-holds-january-camp-p162533-preview-1 |title=Canada Soccer's Men's National Team holds January camp |website=Canada Soccer |date=January 3, 2020 |access-date=January 3, 2020 |archive-date=January 3, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200103182520/https://www.canadasoccer.com/canada-soccer-s-men-s-national-team-holds-january-camp-p162533-preview-1 |url-status=dead }}</ref> On January 10, 2020, he made his debut as a substitute against Barbados.<ref>{{cite web |title=Canadian men's soccer comfortably dispatches Barbados in friendly rematch |url=https://www.cbc.ca/sports/soccer/team-canada-soccer-barbados-friendly-1.5423512 |publisher=[[CBC Sports]] |date=January 10, 2020 |access-date=January 10, 2020}}</ref>

In June 2023, Shaffelburg was called up to Canada's squad for the [[2023 CONCACAF Gold Cup]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://onesoccer.ca/a/roster-drop-shaffelburg-ahmed-and-mc-graw-add-fresh-look-to-canmnt-gold-cup-squad|title=GOLD CUP ROSTER: Shaffelburg, Ahmed, McGraw bring new look to CanMNT|date=June 19, 2023|publisher=[[OneSoccer]]|access-date=2026-05-04}}</ref> On July 9 he scored his first goal for Canada during the quarter-finals of the tournament against the [[United States men's national soccer team|United States]]. The match ended in a 2–2 draw, though Canada lost 3–2 in the ensuing [[Penalty shoot-out (association football)|penalty shoot-out]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://canpl.ca/article/match-analysis-canmnt-heartbroken-in-gold-cup-qf-penalty-shootout-vs-usa|date=July 10, 2023|title=Match Analysis: CanMNT heartbroken in Gold Cup QF penalty shootout vs. USA|first=Charlie|last=O'Connor-Clarke|publisher=[[Canadian Premier League]]|access-date=2026-05-04}}</ref>

In June 2024, Shaffelburg was named in Canada's 26-man roster for the [[2024 Copa América]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://canadasoccer.com/news/canmnt-announce-2024-copa-america-roster/|title=CANMNT ANNOUNCE 2024 COPA AMÉRICA ROSTER|date=June 15, 2024|publisher=[[Canadian Soccer Association]]|access-date=2026-05-04}}</ref> In Canada's second group match of the tournament, he assisted [[Jonathan David]], who scored Canada's first ever goal at the tournament in a 1–0 victory over [[Peru national football team|Peru]]; this was Canada's first ever win in the competition.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.cbc.ca/sports/soccer/canada-peru-copa-america-recap-june-25-1.7246256 |title=Jonathan David lifts Canada over Peru for 1st-ever win at Copa America |publisher=[[CBC Sports]] |date=June 25, 2024 |access-date=June 26, 2024}}</ref> In their quarter-final match against [[Venezuela national football team|Venezuela]], he scored for Canada in a 1–1 draw, which they would go on to win on penalties.<ref>{{Cite news |last=Kloke |first=Joshua |last2=Anzidei |first2=Melanie |last3=Rueter |first3=Jeff |date=2024-07-10 |title=Canada wins penalty shootout against Venezuela, faces rematch with Argentina in Copa America semifinal |url=https://www.nytimes.com/athletic/5619544/2024/07/05/canada-venezuela-copa-america-penalty-shootout/ |access-date=2026-05-04 |work=The New York Times |language=en-US |issn=0362-4331}}</ref> Canada was defeated in the semi-final against Argentina.

==Personal life==
He has been nicknamed [[The Maritimes|Maritime]] [[Lionel Messi|Messi]].<ref>{{cite web|url= https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/nova-scotia/maritime-messi-turning-heads-team-canada-copa-america-1.7250048|title=Maritime Messi turning heads for Team Canada at Copa America|publisher=cbc.ca|date=June 29, 2024|access-date=2026-05-04}}</ref>

